With eight faculties and about  10,000 students  OTH Regensburg  
is one of the largest Universities of Applied Sciences in Bavaria.  
OTH Regensburg offers many  different Bachelor’s, Master’s, and  
other post graduate pro grammes.  
 
You are welcome to visit our website at www.oth-regensburg.de  
or the university campus where our International Office and  
academic  departments will provide you with all the information  
you may need for your studies in Regensburg. Welcome weeks,  
tutors, our Buddy Programme, and housing support are additio -
nal offers that will help you with adjusting to life in Regensburg,  
right from the  beginning.  
Our university is renowned for its outstanding research and  
the  high quality of teaching. It has an excellent reputation for  
 degree programmes designed to provide you with the knowledge  
and skills that will enhance your future employment opportuni -
ties. The city of Regensburg is known for being a friendly and  
 welcoming place with a vibrant  cultural life.  
 
I am sure you will find living in Regensburg and studying at our  
Technical University of Applied Science an exciting and stimu -
lating experience.  
We look forward to meeting you at OTH Regensburg.  
 
 
 
 
Prof. Dr. Ralph Schneider  
President of OTH Regensburg
WELCOME TO OSTBAYERISCHE  
TECHNISCHE HOCHSCHULE REGENSBURG  
(OTH REGENSBURG)

BEFORE ARRIVING IN REGENSBURG  
 
 
WHERE WILL I STAY DURING MY TIME IN REGENSBURG?  
 
We will provide you with application forms for student housing.  
After you have returned both “the  application for accommoda -
tion”  and “acceptance of housing” (housing-international@oth-  
regensburg.de) of OTH Regensburg we will try to reserve an  
 accommodation for you (depending on availability).  Exchange  
students who have received a confirmation for housing, are  
asked to pay a non- refundable reservation fee of € 60 and a  
 deposit of € 350 (the deposit is  refundable at the end of the  
stay). You usually need to transfer the sum before your arrival to  
 Regensburg.  
We do not recommend students to come to Regensburg with-
out first having reserved accommodation through the Inter -
national Office. Finding a furnished room on the  private market  
for such a short period of time is very difficult. Furthermore,  
landlords and estate agents often charge additional fees and  
deposits for rooms and these are generally unfurnished.  
For organisational reasons, it is not possible to give you the  
exact name and address of your student hall of residence  
 before your arrival in Regensburg.  
 
 
WHAT DO THE ROOMS LOOK LIKE?  
 
The International Office reserves single rooms in various student  
halls of residence. These rooms differ in rent, size and furnishing.  
In general, the rooms are furnished with a bed, a desk, a chair,  
a bookshelf, and a wardrobe. Please bring your own bed linen!  
In some dormitories you can also rent the  bedding (for about €  
75). The voltage is 220 V. In most halls of residence, students  
have to share a bathroom and a kitchen.  In some student resi -
dences, you will have internet access through WiFi or LAN cable;  
in some halls of residence, you will have to take care of the  
 internet access yourself. Please bring your own internet cable!  
Every student hall of residence is equipped with washing  
 machines and dryers. Irons and ironing  boards are not provided.  
It should also be noted that  tokens (Waschmarken) are needed  
for the  washing and drying machines. These can be obtained  
from the caretaker (Haus meister) of your  student  residence.  
Monthly rents for a room range between €250 and €360. Food  
is not included in the rent and student  residences are not pro -
vided with  cafe terias or canteens. How ever, most have food and  
drink vending machines. For more information about accommo -
dation please contact the  International Office: housing-inter -
national@oth-regensburg.de or see www.stwno.de.

HOW HIGH ARE THE LIVING  EXPENSES IN REGENSBURG?  
 
Most students need a minimum of about  € 900 per month for  
 living  including rent. Per semester you also have to pay a student  
union fee (approximately € 170), which includes the public  
 transport semester ticket. Together with the reservation fee and  
deposit for housing, the student union fee normally needs to be  
transferred before arrival.  
Please bring enough money in the  beginning to cover your ex -
penses since you have to pay the rent for the first month shortly  
after your arrival in Regensburg. Please also take into consider-
ation the fact that it usually takes two weeks for money to be  
transferred from a foreign bank to an  account in Germany.  
 
CREDIT CARD OR CASH?  
 
In Germany it is still easier to pay in cash or with a European  
debit card (“EC-Karte“). Credit cards are not used as frequently  
as in other countries but the international ones (Visa, Master,  
etc) are mostly accepted. Neve rtheless, you have to pay your  
rent by transferring money via a German or European bank  
 account in  Regensburg.  
 
VISA (IF APPLICABLE)  
 
EU exchange programme students  do not need a visa for stu -
dying in Germany. However, they have to register at the local  
 registry office (Bürgerbüro) within a week of moving into the  
student residence.  
 
Most non-EU students  need a student visa (Visum zu Studien -
zwecken)  issued by a diplomatic representation of the Federal  
Republic of Germany in the student’s home country (embassy  
or consulate). Upon arrival in Regensburg all non-EU students  
have to register at the “Bürgerzentrum der Stadt Regensburg –  
Abteilung für Ausländerangelegenheiten” (local Foreigners’  
 Office) – to get a  residence permit (Aufenthaltstitel). The Inter -
national Office helps all exchange students of OTH Regensburg  
with registration matters.  
Please be aware that it is required to bring financial proof for  
ensuring the means of subsistence during your stay in Germany.  
Please inform yourself about  the current minimum amount  
 regarding the financial proof.  
You should not enter the country as a  tourist! A tourist visa  
cannot be transformed into a student visa or residence permit  
after your arrival in Germany.  
Your passport has to be valid for the entire period of time to be  
spent in Germany, otherwise you will have to go home in the  
middle of your stay to renew it.

HEALTH INSURANCE  
 
All students are subject to compulsory health insurance.  
 
If you are a citizen of the EU  or a country that has a health  
 insurance agreement with Germany, you need to contact the  
 relevant office in your country, in order to obtain the European  
Health Insurance Card (EHIC) or an equivalent document. You  
need this as proof of your health insurance here in Regensburg.  
It is absolutely necessary that you inquire about this document  
before coming to Regensburg! Please check whether your coun -
try concluded social security agreements with Germany.  
 
Students coming from all other countries have to show proof  
of health insurance coverage for the duration of their stay in  
Germany in order to obtain a residence permit (Aufenthaltstitel).  
 
There are two options to take out insurance:  
You can take out private health insurance for the duration of  
your stay in Germany with sufficient coverage.  
According to German law the following treatments must be  
 covered by your health insurance policy:  
1.medical and dental treatment  
2.prescription medication, bandages and other materials  
3.necessary in aiding recovery  
4.treatment in hospital  
5.medical treatment with regard to rehabilitation  
6.pregnancy treatment and birth  
7.ambulance service and transportation  
 
The decision whether or not a particular health insurance cover-
age can be accepted is made by the city’s immigration office.  
 
On the other hand you can take out insurance by a statutory  
 health insurance company in Germany.  
 
We advise all non-EU students to accept the German  
statutory health insurance coverage.  
 
Admission to the university is a prerequisite for obtaining statu -
tory health insurance coverage (proved by presenting the letter  
of acceptance).  
Most students choose the op tion to insure themselves with a  
 statutory health insurance company upon arrival to Regensburg.  
The monthly fee will be around € 90.

The insurance policy starts with the day of enrolment. Therefore,  
please make sure that you also cover the period of time between  
arrival and enrolment date by an adequate health insurance  
 coverage e.g. private travel insurance.  
 
On campus there is a statutory health insurance company. For  
more information please contact the International Office.  
  
Students older than 30 have to buy a private health insurance  
policy. In this case you should ask for information at the Inter -
national Office.  
 
 
 
PRIVATE LIABILITY INSURANCE  
 
This is not obligatory, but we strongly recommend you to take  
out an appropriate private liability insurance policy for the time  
of your stay in Germany.  
Personal liability insurance covers you in cases of accidental  
 damage to a third party or their property. In Germany, you are  
legally responsible for any damages caused to others by your  
person. Therefore, it is one of the most important insurances one  
should hold when living in Germany.  
Please check whether you already hold a personal liability insur-
ance in your home country and whether it also provides coverage  
for the time that you stay in Germany. Liability insurance can be  
taken out online upon arrival.  
 
 
 
HOW DO I GET TO REGENSBURG?  
 
There is no airport in Regensburg. The closest one is  Munich  
 Airport, but you can also fly to Nürnberg/Nuremberg or Frank -
furt. Trains leave regularly from all these airports to  Regensburg.  
 
If you land at Munich airport (Flughafen München), you can take  
a direct train to Regensburg. Information: www.bahn.de  
Or you can book a coach through internet www.flixbus.co.uk  
Another possibility to get from Munich airport to Regensburg is  
the airport shuttle bus which should be booked online at least  
three days in advance. Information: www.airportliner.com

UPON ARRIVAL IN REGENSBURG  
 
 
 
Go to the International Office of OTH Regensburg, Galgenberg -
straße 30, room D 115 and D 113, where you will receive your  rental  
agreement, your keys and important papers for your stay. Open-
ing hours for the recommended days of arrival are Monday – 
 Friday from 9 am to 4 pm.  
 
HOW DO I GET TO THE INTERNATIONAL OFFICE?  
 
Go to the central bus station at Albertstraße (about two  minutes  
from the train station). Take bus no.11 (direction: Burgweinting)  
or bus no. 6 (direction: Klinikum). You need to get off at the bus  
stop: “OTH Regensburg” (bus no.11) or bus stop: “Tech Cam -
pus/OTH“ (bus no. 6). The International Office is in the  Lecture  
Hall Forum building D on the 1st floor, room no. D 11 3– 119. 
 
WHAT SHALL I DO IF I ARRIVE IN REGENSBURG  
ON THE WEEKEND OR LATER THAN 4 P.M.?  
 
In that case, please get in touch with the International  Office in  
time to make the necessary arrangements. If no contact has  
been made, you might have to stay in a hotel or a youth  hostel  
over the weekend. For more information see:  
www.regensburg.de  
 
WHAT SHALL I DO IF I COME BY CAR?  
 
If you come by car, you should drive directly to OTH Regensburg.  
Take the Regensburg-Kumpfmühl exit on the motorway from  
“München” to “Weiden” (A93) and follow the signs to the  
“Hochschule/OTH”.

Tutors for exchange students  
The tutors help the exchange students with organisational  
 matters during their stay in Re gensburg and organise activities,  
like a  weekly get-together, trips  etc. Should you need help  
upon arrival, please contact them via E-mail:  
tutors-international@oth-regensburg.de  
 
 
LIBRARY  
 
For the library you will get your student ID card, which includes  
 Mensa, library and semester transport ticket.  
bibliothek.oth-regensburg.de/en/  
 
 
INTERNET  
 
All students registered at OTH Regensburg have access to the  
internet and web-based e-mail. On campus there are several  
computer labs (Cip Pools), from which you will be able to access  
e-mail and the internet. If you bring your laptop and a LAN-
cable, you can also connect from the student halls of residence.  
Please be aware that WiFi is not provided in every student hall  
of residence.

CAFETERIA  
 
There is a cafeteria on every site of the University where you can  
get snacks, salads, coffee, and other food items.  
 
 
MENSA – THE STUDENTS’ DINING HALL  
 
Students normally cook their own meals or eat in the students’  
dining hall (Mensa) on the university site. The dining hall  offers  
warm meals from Monday to Friday twice a day (for lunch and  
dinner). On the internet you can find the opening hours of the  
dining halls: www.stwno.de/en/  
In the students’ dining hall and in all cafeterias you pay with  
your student ID. It works like a debit card. There are machines in  
the entrance hall to the Mensa and in the cafeterias in which  
you put your money to top up your card. Paying cash is usually  
not accepted.  
 
 
BUDDY PROGRAMME  
 
You are warmly invited to join our international buddy pro -
gramme. Its main aim is to promote cultural exchange between  
German and international students. For more information please  
check our website:  
www.oth-regensburg.de/en/study/international-office/  
studying-in-regensburg/exchange-students/buddy-programme/  
international-buddys .  
You have to register for our Buddy Programme through our  
buddy tool a few weeks before you arrive to Regensburg.  
Your assigned German buddy will support you with any queries,  
questions or in case of problems before and during your stay.

IMPORTANT THINGS TO KNOW  
 
 
CHOICE OF COURSES  
 
You will find the timetable for each faculty on the website of  
OTH Regensburg www.oth-regensburg.de  at the beginning of  
each  semester. Please speak with tutors, your buddy and other  
students about the courses to find out which documents  
(scripts, books, exercises and exams) you will need. You should  
also speak with the professor teaching the course and ask  
him/her if the content of the  lessons is enough or if he/she  
 recommends any books or  further excercises.  
A list of current courses that are taught in English:   
www.oth- regensburg.de/en/study/international-office/  
studying-in -regensburg/courses-in-english  
 
 
HOW TO GET AROUND  
 
By Train:  People, who plan to travel through Germany by train,  
can seek information about special offers at the “Deutsche  
 Bundesbahn“ (such as “BahnCard“, “Wochenendticket“, “Bay -
ernticket“ etc.). Information: www.bahn.de  
 Public Transport:  With your valid student ID card, public trans -
port within Regensburg and during the semester is free of  
charge. All buses in town and in the surrounding area up to  
50km (trains included) can be used. The fee for the  ticket is  
 already included in the “Studentenwerks beitrag” when registe -
ring. For more information see www.rvv.de 
By Car:  Not necessary, because the distances are small and you  
can easily reach every destination by bus or by bike. Most streets  
in the city centre are closed for cars and there are no parking  
spaces available.  
 By Bike:  Regensburg is excellent for cycling because of its cycle  
paths. A bicycle is the best way to get around in the city and to  
get to campus. You can buy inexpensive second-hand bikes at  
the flea-market (every weekend) or in the bike shops. Usually,  
you can sell your bike without any problems before you return to  
your home country. At week ends you can also go for wonderful  
cycling tours in and around Regensburg.  
Information: www.bayernbike.de

DO I NEED TO OPEN A BANK ACCOUNT IN REGENSBURG?  
 
If you are living in a dormitory the monthly rent and also your  
health insurance fee will be taken  automatically from your bank  
account.  
 Normally students from EU countries  can use their bank  
 account at home on condition that  
nThey are the account holders  
nThe home bank supports SEPA direct debit mandates and accepts  
nEnglish-language SEPA mandates  
Students from Non-EU countries  have to open a German or  
 European bank account upon arrival. There are also a few online  
banks where you can open a European bank account online. For  
this you will need your passport or ID card, your home tax ID  
(TIN), your address in  Germany and a confirmation that you are  
a student at OTH  Regensburg.  
Under no circumstances can the rent be paid by credit card. It  
should also be noted that banks are closed on weekends. 
 
PUBLIC SERVICE BROADCASTING 
To make public service broadcasting available for everyone, the  
German public service broadcasters are financed by the licence  
fee. This fee amounts to about € 19 per month and is levied for  
each residence – regardless of how many people live there or how  
many devices they use.  
More information under  www.rundfunkbeitrag.de/welcome/   
 
POST OFFICE  
 
Most post offices are open from 8 or 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Information  
about costs for sending items can be obtained at the post office  
or on www.deutschepost.de . The Main Post Office: Bahnhof -
straße 16, 93047 Regensburg

OPENING HOURS OF SHOPS  
 
In Germany, shops are usually open Monday to Friday from  
8a.m. to 8p.m. Smaller shops, however, often do close earlier,  
for example at 6.30 p.m. On Saturdays shops open only in the  
mornings, but many are open from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. or even  
8p.m. in the city centre. On Sundays shops are closed.  
 
 
E-MAIL  
 
As a registered student y ou have access to e-mail at the univer -
sity. Please read your e-mails regularly. They provide you with  
all important and relevant information on your studies.  
 
 
JOBS  
 
EU-nationals can work in Germany without a work permit. A  
 residence permit for the purpose of studying allows  non-EU  
 students to take on jobs which do not exceed 120 days or 240  
half-days per year. Students may also take on student jobs with  
no time limit at the university or at other academic establish -
ments. If you are looking for a job beside your studies, you can  
find out about what is available at the employment office  
 Regensburg or in the local news papers (Mittelbayerische Zei -
tung, Wochenblatt) or on the internet:  
www.arbeitsagentur.de  or www. jobs.meinestadt.de/regensburg    
 
Studentische Arbeitsvermittlung

Galgenbergstr. 24 · 93053 Regensburg

SPORT FACILITIES AT THE UNIVERSITY  
 
All students have access to the Univer sity Sport Centre. It is used  
for both personal leisure and for fitness programmes. You can  
choose from more than 50 different kinds of sport and you only  
need to top up your student ID card and register for the sport  
ticket at one of the terminals at OTH Regensburg. For some  
other kinds of sport such as golf, canoeing,  riding, sauna, swim -
ming, diving, tennis etc. you have to pay an extra fee.  
For detailed information see Sports Programme from the  uni-
versity, info boards at the sports centre or on the internet  
www.uni-regensburg.de/sports/home/index.html  
 
Sportzentrum der Universität

Tel.: +49 (0)941 943-2517
